english:
  title: Dedicatory Verse for Raising the Beam of the Main Hall of Yeongyeong Palace
  author: Lim Jong-bi
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When King Cheng of Zhou built the city of Luoyi, the Book of History praised his reverence for Heaven's grace. When the Duke of Wey constructed the Palace of Chu, the Book of Poetry celebrated his mastery of proper timing. Was this only true in ancient days? Is it not so now? The rise and fall of the Way are bound to the workings of fate; the flourishing and decline of all things are tied to the seasons of Heaven.

    Consider our realm: through successive generations, its glory increases. How magnificent! The palaces that crown the eastern quarter—these are halls of seclusion fit for an emperor. Peaks rise as screens on every side, and waters wind their way in circles round about. The beauty of mountains and rivers mirrors the Isles of the Immortals above the sea; the halls and towers, deep and solemn, are like a cosmos contained within a jar. Long the seasons passed, and long did wind and rain work their ruin upon these walls. For years they lay neglected, awaiting restoration.

    Humble I am to reflect: Our Lord embodies the vast and fathomless virtue of Heaven. He stands upon the foundations laid by generations before. With great deeds and arduous labors accomplished, he has not rested in the comfort of Heaven's mandate, but has pacified disorder and restored righteousness, bringing us to this glorious day. Yet he harbors no thought of ease, but rather grows ever more determined in his vision of renewal and restoration.

    Thus he turned his mind to the building of this palace, gathering all his focus and care. Following the pattern of "Sigan," the beams and pillars rise; taking the form of the "Great Vigor" hexagram, roof peaks crown and eaves protect below. The master craftsmen were commanded, the wood was measured, old foundations were opened, and the dwelling expanded. The work of construction proceeded—not exceeding a few months—and behold! How tall and beautiful! Nearly a hundred chambers completed. Though our nation is ancient, the Mandate is ever new. Though the labor is but half of what the ancients undertook, the achievement shall surely be doubled.

    On an auspicious day, we gather to raise the great beam. As the rafters near completion, the swallows come to offer their celebration. No orchestral music plays, yet the phoenix knows to come and dance. From this moment forward, the work of good governance begins.

    *Hearkening youths! Lift high the eastern beam!*
    *The great timber stands proud as a rainbow in the sky.*
    *The fairy palaces of Penglai open wide their gates,*
    *And all beneath heaven gaze joyful on the sun and moon.*

    *Hearkening youths! Lift high the western beam!*
    *Reaching toward heaven's height, it strides across clouds and mist.*
    *A hundred lands, crowned and belted, bow to such virtue,*
    *And in the parasol tree once more, the phoenix makes its nest.*

    *Hearkening youths! Lift high the southern beam!*
    *A thousand layers of splendid halls stand solemn and profound.*
    *The sacred writings sealed in gold, the time of great offering draws near—*
    *Mount Song shall echo with ten thousand voices crying "Long may he reign!"*

    *Hearkening youths! Lift high the northern beam!*
    *Auspicious vapors rise and coil about the Purple Pole Star bright.*
    *Wondrous blessings dwell within these halls as if by divine design,*
    *The Jade Gate stands at peace, the dust of conflict settles into calm.*

    *Hearkening youths! Lift high the beam above!*
    *Ten thousand tiles lie scaled like fish upon the eaves so grand.*
    *Who has moved the Purple Subtlety Palace to this place?*
    *Gold and jade exchange their light in dazzling interplay.*

    *Hearkening youths! Gaze down below the beam!*
    *The auspicious wind blows soft upon the mandarin duck tiles,*
    *The promise of Great Peace settles here in perfect measure.*
    *[The remainder is lost to time.]
  footnotes:
    - The "Book of History" (Shu Jing) and "Book of Poetry" (Shi Jing) are foundational Chinese classics often cited to validate imperial undertakings through historical precedent.
    - The Isles of Penglai (Penglai Shan) represent the legendary realm of immortals in Chinese mythology, suggesting the palace rivals the abodes of the divine.
    - The "Sigan" poem (from the Shi Jing) describes the proper construction of palaces with attention to ritual propriety. The "Great Vigor" hexagram (Dazhuang) from the I Ching represents strength and architectural harmony.
    - The phoenix and mandarin ducks are auspicious symbols of imperial virtue and conjugal harmony in East Asian tradition.
